e Mauthausen trial reveals a troubling and seldom-recognized face of American postwar justice—one characterized by rapid proceedings, lax rules of evidence, and questionable interrogations.Although the better-known Nuremberg trials are often regarded as epitomizing American judicial ideals, these trials were in fact the exception to the rule. Instead, as Tomaz Jardim convincingly demonstrates, the rough justice of the Mauthausen trial remains indicative of the most common—and yet least understood—American approach to war crimes prosecution. The Mauthausen Trial forces reflection on the implications of compromising legal standards in order to guarantee that guilty people do not walk free.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aAtrocities. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xAustriaxAustriaxGermanyxDachau. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zAustria. 0aMauthausen Trial, Dachau, Germany, 1946. 0aRecht. 0aTrials (Genocide)xGermanyxDachau. 0aTrials (Genocide)zGermanyzDachau. 0aTrials (Genocide). 0aWar crime trialsxGermanyxDachau. 0aWar crime trialszGermanyzDachau. 0aWar crime trials. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE UND GESCHICHTE 2011z9783110261257oZDB-23-DGE08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406312940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn